feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/DiscoverMag?a=WlLX7ws-_xo:niEtG7HGzw8:qj6IDK7rITs\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/DiscoverMag?d=qj6IDK7rITs\" border=\"0\"></img></a><a href=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/DiscoverMag?a=WlLX7ws-_xo:niEtG7HGzw8:F7zBnMyn0Lo\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/DiscoverMag?i=WlLX7ws-_xo:niEtG7HGzw8:F7zBnMyn0Lo\" border=\"0\"></img></a><a href=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/DiscoverMag?a=WlLX7ws-_xo:niEtG7HGzw8:V_sGLiPBpWU\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/DiscoverMag?i=WlLX7ws-_xo:niEtG7HGzw8:V_sGLiPBpWU\" border=\"0\"></img></a></div><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/DiscoverMag/~4/WlLX7ws-_xo\" height=\"1\" width=\"1\"/>") (feedburner:origLink nil "http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/80beats/~3/Oug9ekqhxM4/"))) ("Arecibo gives comet some radar love | Bad Astronomy" "<p>Using a giant radio telescope like a cop’s radar gun, <a rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"http://www.jpl.nasa.gov/news/news.cfm?release=2010-358\">astronomers have made some pretty cool images</a> of the nucleus of the comet Hartley 2:</p><p><a rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"http://www.jpl.nasa.gov/news/news.cfm?release=2010-358\"><img src=\"http://blogs.discovermagazine.com/badastronomy/files/2010/10/arecibo_hartley2.jpg\" alt=\"arecibo_hartley2\" title=\"arecibo_hartley2\" width=\"470\" height=\"350\" class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-23297\"/></a><br clear=\"all\"></p><p><a rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"http://blogs.discovermagazine.com/badastronomy/2010/10/08/three-views-to-a-comet/\">Hartley 2</a> is a comet that is currently very close to the Earth as these things go: last week it passed us at a distance of about 18 million km (11 million miles). Astronomers took advantage of the close pass to ping the comet with radar pulses. By timing exactly how long it took the pulses to go from the telescope to the comet and back to Earth, they can create a map of the comet’s shape and other characteristics — something like how dolphins and bats use echolocation to map their surroundings… though, as Emily Lakdawalla at The Planetary Society Blog explains, <a rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"http://www.planetary.org/blog/article/00002462/\">it’s a bit more complicated</a>.</p><p>From the images, it looks like the nucleus — the solid, central part of a comet — is highly elongated, about 2.2 km (1.4 miles) in length, and rotates once every 18 hours. We’ve only seen a handful of comets up close, and in general the nuclei are potato-shaped, so this one fits that description. <a rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"http://www.naic.edu/~pradar/103P/\">The image</a> has a scale of about 75 meters per pixel.</p><p>These observations were made to help out <a rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"http://blogs.discovermagazine.com/badastronomy/2008/02/10/epoxi-sticks-like-glue-to-extrasolar-planets/\">the EPOXI space mission</a>, which will pass just 700 km (420 miles) from the nucleus of Hartley 2 on November 4. That means we’ll be getting some really cool close-up images and data from the comet very soon! Stay Tuned.</p><p><br clear=\"all\"></p><p><a rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"http://feedads.g.doubleclick.net/~a/7xN3uzqjlGO3A2yuqLGU7d4bLWs/0/da\"><img src=\"http://feedads.g.doubleclick.net/~a/7xN3uzqjlGO3A2yuqLGU7d4bLWs/0/di\" border=\"0\" ismap></a><br/><a rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"http://feedads.g.doubleclick.net/~a/7xN3uzqjlGO3A2yuqLGU7d4bLWs/1/da\"><img src=\"http://feedads.g.doubleclick.net/~a/7xN3uzqjlGO3A2yuqLGU7d4bLWs/1/di\" border=\"0\" ismap></a></p><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/BadAstronomyBlog/~4/1ggApvfDxSI\" height=\"1\" width=\"1\"/><div class=\"feedflare\"><a href=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/DiscoverMag?a=fp3m8YE6gg0:jFDWz4WxmlI:yIl2AUoC8zA\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/DiscoverMag?d=yIl2AUoC8zA\" border=\"0\"></img></a><a href=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/DiscoverMag?a=fp3m8YE6gg0:jFDWz4WxmlI:qj6IDK7rITs\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/DiscoverMag?d=qj6IDK7rITs\" border=\"0\"></img></a><a href=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/DiscoverMag?a=fp3m8YE6gg0:jFDWz4WxmlI:F7zBnMyn0Lo\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/DiscoverMag?i=fp3m8YE6gg0:jFDWz4WxmlI:F7zBnMyn0Lo\" border=\"0\"></img></a><a href=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/DiscoverMag?a=fp3m8YE6gg0:jFDWz4WxmlI:V_sGLiPBpWU\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/DiscoverMag?i=fp3m8YE6gg0:jFDWz4WxmlI:V_sGLiPBpWU\" border=\"0\"></img></a></div><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/DiscoverMag/~4/fp3m8YE6gg0\" height=\"1\" width=\"1\"/>" "http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/DiscoverMag/~3/fp3m8YE6gg0/" (19658 63879) obsolete 13 nil nil ((title nil "Arecibo gives comet some radar love | Bad Astronomy") (link nil "http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/DiscoverMag/~3/fp3m8YE6gg0/") (description nil "Using a giant radio telescope like a cop&#8217;s radar gun, astronomers have made some pretty cool images of the nucleus of the comet Hartley 2: Hartley 2 is a comet that is currently very close to the Earth as these things go: last week it passed us at a distance of about 18 million km (11 [...]") (guid ((isPermaLink . "false")) "http://blogs.discovermagazine.com/badastronomy/?p=23296") (pubDate nil "Fri, 29 Oct 2010 09:42:47 -0700") (content:encoded nil "<p>Using a giant radio telescope like a cop&#8217;s radar gun, <a rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"http://www.jpl.nasa.gov/news/news.cfm?release=2010-358\">astronomers have made some pretty cool images</a> of the nucleus of the comet Hartley 2:</p><p><a rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"http://www.jpl.nasa.gov/news/news.cfm?release=2010-358\"><img src=\"http://blogs.discovermagazine.com/badastronomy/files/2010/10/arecibo_hartley2.jpg\" alt=\"arecibo_hartley2\" title=\"arecibo_hartley2\" width=\"470\" height=\"350\" class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-23297\"/></a><br clear=\"all\"></p><p><a rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"http://blogs.discovermagazine.com/badastronomy/2010/10/08/three-views-to-a-comet/\">Hartley 2</a> is a comet that is currently very close to the Earth as these things go: last week it passed us at a distance of about 18 million km (11 million miles). Astronomers took advantage of the close pass to ping the comet with radar pulses. By timing exactly how long it took the pulses to go from the telescope to the comet and back to Earth, they can create a map of the comet&#8217;s shape and other characteristics &#8212; something like how dolphins and bats use echolocation to map their surroundings&#8230; though, as Emily Lakdawalla at The Planetary Society Blog explains, <a rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"http://www.planetary.org/blog/article/00002462/\">it&#8217;s a bit more complicated</a>.</p><p>From the images, it looks like the nucleus &#8212; the solid, central part of a comet &#8212; is highly elongated, about 2.2 km (1.4 miles) in length, and rotates once every 18 hours. We&#8217;ve only seen a handful of comets up close, and in general the nuclei are potato-shaped, so this one fits that description. <a rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"http://www.naic.edu/~pradar/103P/\">The image</a> has a scale of about 75 meters per pixel.</p><p>These observations were made to help out <a rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"http://blogs.discovermagazine.com/badastronomy/2008/02/10/epoxi-sticks-like-glue-to-extrasolar-planets/\">the EPOXI space mission</a>, which will pass just 700 km (420 miles) from the nucleus of Hartley 2 on November 4. That means we&#8217;ll be getting some really cool close-up images and data from the comet very soon! Stay Tuned.</p><p><br clear=\"all\"></p><p><a rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"http://feedads.g.doubleclick.net/~a/7xN3uzqjlGO3A2yuqLGU7d4bLWs/0/da\"><img src=\"http://feedads.g.doubleclick.net/~a/7xN3uzqjlGO3A2yuqLGU7d4bLWs/0/di\" border=\"0\" ismap></a><br/><a rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"http://feedads.g.doubleclick.net/~a/7xN3uzqjlGO3A2yuqLGU7d4bLWs/1/da\"><img src=\"http://feedads.g.doubleclick.net/~a/7xN3uzqjlGO3A2yuqLGU7d4bLWs/1/di\" border=\"0\" ismap></a></p><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/BadAstronomyBlog/~4/1ggApvfDxSI\" height=\"1\" width=\"1\"/><div class=\"feedflare\"><a href=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/DiscoverMag?a=fp3m8YE6gg0:jFDWz4WxmlI:yIl2AUoC8zA\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/DiscoverMag?d=yIl2AUoC8zA\" border=\"0\"></img></a><a href=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/DiscoverMag?a=fp3m8YE6gg0:jFDWz4WxmlI:qj6IDK7rITs\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/DiscoverMag?d=qj6IDK7rITs\" border=\"0\"></img></a><a href=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/DiscoverMag?a=fp3m8YE6gg0:jFDWz4WxmlI:F7zBnMyn0Lo\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/DiscoverMag?i=fp3m8YE6gg0:jFDWz4WxmlI:F7zBnMyn0Lo\" border=\"0\"></img></a><a href=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/DiscoverMag?a=fp3m8YE6gg0:jFDWz4WxmlI:V_sGLiPBpWU\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/DiscoverMag?i=fp3m8YE6gg0:jFDWz4WxmlI:V_sGLiPBpWU\" border=\"0\"></img></a></div><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/DiscoverMag/~4/fp3m8YE6gg0\" height=\"1\" width=\"1\"/>") (feedburner:origLink nil "http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/BadAstronomyBlog/~3/1ggApvfDxSI/"))) ("Give, Give, Give | Cosmic Variance" "<p>It’s been days since we’ve hit people up for our <a rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"http://www.donorschoose.org/donors/viewChallenge.html?id=80652&max=50\">Donors Choose 2010 Challenge</a>. As you know, this is <a rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"http://blogs.discovermagazine.com/cosmicvariance/2010/10/12/donorschoose-challenge-2010/\">our favorite cause</a>. It’s also <a rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"http://www.colbertnation.com/the-colbert-report-videos/361458/october-07-2010/donorschoose-org-fear-drawings\">Stephen Colbert’s favorite</a>, as if you needed any extra motivation.</p><table style='font:11px arial;color:#333;background-color:#f5f5f5;' cellpadding='0' cellspacing='0' width='360' height='353'><tbody><tr style='background-color:#e5e5e5;' valign='middle'><td style='padding:2px 1px 0px 5px;'><a rel=\"nofollow\" style='color:#333;text-decoration:none;font-weight:bold;' target=\"_blank\" href='http://www.colbertnation.com'>The Colbert Report</a></td><td style='padding:2px 5px 0px 5px;text-align:right;font-weight:bold;'>Mon – Thurs 11:30pm / 10:30c</td></tr><tr style='height:14px;' valign='middle'><td style='padding:2px 1px 0px 5px;' colspan='2' style='color:#333;text-decoration:none;font-weight:bold;'>DonorsChoose.org Fear Drawings<a rel=\"nofollow\"></td></tr><tr style='height:14px;background-color:#353535;' valign='middle'><td colspan='2' style='padding:2px 5px 0px 5px;width:360px;overflow:hidden;text-align:right;'><a rel=\"nofollow\" style='color:#96deff;text-decoration:none;font-weight:bold;' target=\"_blank\" href='http://www.colbertnation.com/'>www.colbertnation.com</a></td></tr><tr valign='middle'><td style='padding:0px;' colspan='2'><iframe class=\"embeddedvideo\" src='http://media.mtvnservices.com/mgid:cms:item:comedycentral.com:361458' width='360' height='301' type='application/x-shockwave-flash'></iframe></td></tr><tr style='height:18px;' valign='middle'><td style='padding:0px;' colspan='2'><table style='margin:0px;text-align:center;' cellpadding='0' cellspacing='0' width='100%' height='100%'><tr valign='middle'><td style='padding:3px;width:33%;'><a rel=\"nofollow\" style='font:10px arial;color:#333;text-decoration:none;' target=\"_blank\" href='http://www.colbertnation.com/full-episodes/'>Colbert Report Full Episodes</a></td><td style='padding:3px;width:33%;'><a rel=\"nofollow\" style='font:10px arial;color:#333;text-decoration:none;' target=\"_blank\" href='http://www.indecisionforever.com/'>2010 Election</a></td><td style='padding:3px;width:33%;'><a rel=\"nofollow\" style='font:10px arial;color:#333;text-decoration:none;' target=